Notes:

@enumerate 0
@item @ilc{0}
Identity conversion, provided for convenience.  (If the method also accepts an organization, then it
performs the identity conversion only if the organization of the argument matches that requested.)
@item @ilc{1}
Constructs the WB-tree implementation of its type (@code{wb-set} etc.).
@item @ilc{2}
Constructs the CHAMP implementation of its type (@code{ch-set} etc.).
@item @ilc{3}
Has keyword parameter @var{pairs?}.  If true, treats the input elements as pairs (represented as
conses) of a value and a count (multiplicity).
@item @ilc{4}
Has keyword parameter @var{from-type}.  If it's the symbol @code{alist}, treats the input elements as pairs
(as conses) of a value and a count.  Deprecated; use @var{pairs?}.
@item @ilc{5}
Has keyword parameter @var{pair-fn}, defaulting to @code{#'cons}, which specifies the function used
to combine each key/value pair.
@item @ilc{6}
Has keyword parameters @var{key-fn} and @var{value-fn}, used to extract a key/value pair from each
input element.  Defaults are @code{#'car} and @code{#'cdr}.
@item @ilc{7}
If a key occurs more than once in the input, the result will have the value associated with the last
occurrence.
@item @ilc{8}
All keyword arguments are forwarded to @code{make-hash-table}.
@item @ilc{9}
Optimized O(n) algorithm.
@item @ilc{10}
Has keyword parameter @var{from-type}.  If it's the symbol @code{map-to-sets}, the range elements
must all be sets, and the result pairs each domain element with each element of the corresponding
range set.  Otherwise, the result pairs each domain element with the corresponding range element
directly.
@item @ilc{11}
The relation must be a function (must have only one range value per domain value).  @xref{Method
conflicts (2-relation)}.
@item @ilc{12}
Returns a map mapping each domain value to the set of corresponding range values.  The default of
the result is the empty set.
@item @ilc{13}
Constructs a @code{dyn-tuple}.
@item @ilc{14}
Always returns a string (or base-string, if specified).  Signals a @code{non-char-seq-error} if the
seq contains a non-character.  Signals a @code{type-error} if a base-string is specified and it
encounters a non-base character.
@item @ilc{15}
Has keyword parameter @var{compare-fn-name}.  If nonnull, must be a symbol, the name of the comparison
function to be used.  The returned set will be converted, if necessary, to use the specified
function, or to use @code{compare} if one is not specified.
@item @ilc{16}
Has keyword parameters @var{key-compare-fn-name} band @var{val-compare-fn-name}.  If nonnull, these
must be symbols, the names of the key and value comparison functions, respectively, to be used.  The
returned map will be converted, if necessary, to use the specified functions, or to use
@code{compare} for those not specified.
@item @ilc{17}
Has keyword parameter @var{autokey?}.  if true, then any keys of the map that are not instances of
@code{tuple-key} are automatically converted to such instances using @href{Function get-tuple-key,
@code{get-tuple-key}}.
@item @ilc{18}
Has keyword parameter @var{input-sorted?}.  If true, uses an algorithm optimized for the case where
the input is sorted: it runs in O(n) time and is much faster, but is substantially @emph{slower}
than the default algorithm if the input is completely unsorted.  ``Sorted'' here means that the
input is in the same order as the collection being built.  The algorithm's correctness doesn't
depend on the sorting, only its performance; so it's okay if a few elements are out of order.
@item @ilc{19}
Has keyword parameter @var{default}, which specifies the default of the result; if not supplied, the
default is @code{nil}.  Also has keyword parameter @var{no-default?} to specify no default.
@item @ilc{20}
Has keyword parameter @var{default}, which specifies the default of the result; if not supplied, the
default is the same as that of the argument.  Also has keyword parameter @var{no-default?}  to
specify no default.
@item @ilc{21}
@code{sequence} here refers to a CL sequence -- either a list or a vector, unless the implementation
has more sequence subtypes.  FSet's @code{seq} is not a subtype of @code{sequence}.
@item @ilc{22}
O(1), provided the implementation and organization, if applicable, are unchanged.
@item @ilc{23}
Has keyword parameter @var{reverse?}, which if true, reverses the order.
@item @ilc{24}
Has keyword parameter @var{keys-only?}; if true, converts the key sequence to the target type,
omitting the values and ignoring @var{pair-fn}.  If it's true and @var{to-type} is @code{seq} or
@code{wb-seq}, the conversion is O(1).
@end enumerate
